text.77: Talabong: At the start of the pandemic, I was always looking for a new news cycle…. I want to split myself and just do all of them at the same time at hindi ko kaya. It led to burnout. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.78: Ranada: Ako, opposite ni Lian. Kailangan talaga ng shutdown for 2 days. Yung weekend ko is reserved for my baby, my husband, my family. No more looking at Twitter, Facebook. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.79: Buan: Yes, the news cycle gets really exhausting. Pero ang saya-saya niya talaga pag-usapan. This has become so embedded in our lives…. When one news cycle gets exhausting, you move to the next cycle. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.80: Cupin: My last question isn't technically about podcasts but about you and about the work that we do. When the news cycle is exhausting, what do you do? #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.81: Gavilan: In my podcast, the primary language is conversational Filipino-English. When I talk to people, conversational English. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.82: Rock out with Happy Three Friends as they play on this lockdown #LiveJam TONIGHT, October 10, at 8 pm! #HappyThreeFriendsxLiveJam https://t.co/CY7Z7IJa2W
text.83: Talabong: I feel like in podcasting, reporters assume the role of the narrator the most. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.84: Talabong: Sa akin, for podcasts, it gives reporters so much power. This medium gives us so much power because it's a new medium for us. It's so unexplored. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.85: Buan: I hope to take that experience and share it with a larger group of audience. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.86: Buan: The idea is those coffee shop conversations or inuman conversations or even just casual conversations among lawyers or lawyers explaining it to their non-lawyer friends. They can be as candid as they can be. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.87: Buan: Podcast still requires the same authority of content, the same credibility of analysis. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.88: Buan: What I like about podcasts is that you can be less structured with it. As opposed to what you are required to be when you’re writing a special report or an in-depth. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.89: Ranada: May malaking audience out there and for me, ang dami pang puwedeng gawin especially for political broadcasting. This could be our way to bring politics closer to our generation and to the younger generation. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.90: Ranada: It's a very exciting medium that you can insert a little bit of yourself in it, but also be talking about something bigger, a shared experience that your listener will also relate to because they're in the same reality. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdQb158
text.91: Ranada: Mas may flexibility ka to be yourself and give your thoughts about the topic. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.92: Ranada: Yung podcast, very personal siya na medium. It's your voice talking to another person and they're all alone in their car, or in their room, or wherever, parang your whispering to them, you're sharing your knowledge to them. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.93: Gavilan: Walang pretentions dito. It comes from a place of legit interest of not knowing what's happening, not knowing how everything is put into context. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.94: Gavilan: For me, the big difference is I get to ask all the questions I want and I’m sure it can be delivered in one complete package. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.95: Cupin: How different or the same is working on a podcast compared to long-form stories or preparing a video report? #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.96: Cupin: I feel like when I listen to your broadcast, it shows the years that you've spent, not just in your beats, but in the news. It shows in the kinds of insights that you write or the kinds of insights that you say. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.97: Gavilan: There are also details na hindi maisama sa article. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.98: Buan: There are details you can tell in a podcast which you can otherwise can’t write in a story. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.99: Ranada: The best way to weave those details together and make sense of it all is through a podcast where you can string it with different soundbites across time. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.100: Ranada: May mga little details na at first glance it doesn’t sound important, but if you’ve been covering the beat for a long time, alam mong may significance ‘yun. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.101: Ranada: ‘Yung maganda sa podcast, pwede s'ya i-repurpose sa ibang deliverables as a reporter. I’m also thinking this podcast interview, I can also quote on my in-depth. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.102: Talabong: It’s also a moment to just pause and look at it in the bigger picture. What does this story mean in the bigger scheme of things? #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
text.103: Buan: It’s actually the podcast that kept me sane. #RapplerTalk: https://t.co/K6CXdPTpGy
